        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve"  xml:lang="xpi-Ogam" cert="low" resp="#LH">              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/> <!--change text direction if needed, please-->
                    ᚁᚏ<g ref="#forfid_X"/>ᚌᚐᚃ <persName><name nymRef="#necton">ᚅᚓᚉᚈᚑᚅ</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:up"/>
                    ᚂᚐᚁᚒ<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration"  xml:lang="xpi-Ogam" cert="low" xml:space="preserve" resp="#LH">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/> <!--change text direction if needed, please-->
                    BR<g ref="#forfid_X" type="interpretation_E"/>GAV <persName><name nymRef="#necton">NECTON</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:up"/>
                    LABU<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>The inscription includes the personal name <persName xml:lang="xpi">Necton</persName> (Forsyth 1997, 35).</note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>The inscription is insufficient to produce a translation.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
<p>Information about the stone and its analysis is limited due to the lack of publications. However, as Forsyth (1997, 35) explains, <q><persName xml:lang="xpi">Nechton</persName> or <persName xml:lang="xpi">Neiton</persName> is the well-known Pictish name of saint and kings</q>.</p>
                <p>Forsyth suggests the stone likely served as a boundary marker (ibid.).</p>
            </div>
